<POST>
<POSTER> BryanUT &lt;nestl...@comcast.net&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-10-02T17:15:00 </POSTDATE>
You know engine braking is so effective that on more modern sport
bikes &quot;slipper&quot; clutches are installed to reduce engine braking.

It seems down shifting from high speeds can cause the back end to get
all squirrley.  With engine braking it is impossible to modulate the
braking effect as precisely as with the rear brake itself.

I guess you could up shift to reduce the braking effect and then down
shift again.  I find just using the brakes to be easier.

As a matter of fact a slipper clutch would be a highly desirable
feature on my next bike.

On my sportbike I find just rolling off the throttle in any gear at
most any speed results in pronounced decelleration.
