Maybe. R6's rev to the Moon, though. The latest R6 has a tach that goes up to
18000 RPM.

The older R6 was designed to rev 2000 or 3000 RPM past its 13000 RPM power
peak so the rider didn't have to shift gears in the middle of a long corner.

GXR1000's are designed with the same idea. When you watch the data panel
during a race, you will see that the riders are staying in the lower three
gears and only getting into high gear on the longest straight.

A GSXR1000 will go about 90 to 100 mph in first gear, what does it need the
other gears for on the street?

But racers are always pulling a lot of high RPM and really need that slipper
clutch to take the binding load off the rear suspension when they roll off
the throttle.

When I used to do illegal road racing with a club of sportbike outlaws, I
would always drag the rear brake through tight corners. This upset one rider
who thought that I should get my braking down and then shoot the corner at
whatever entry speed I set up.

I told him that dragging the rear brake was like adding damping to the rear
shocks. I told him that it was like downshifting into passing gear in a car
with an automatic transmission when I wanted to firm up the suspension so the
rear end wouldn't feel like it was floating as I entered a high speed turn.

He wasn't satisfied. He wanted to know why if I needed stiffer shocks I
didn't just install stiffer shocks?

I told the guy that my only choices were the original equipment shocks, Dutch
Koni shocks that were designed for cars, or Boge shocks that were made in
Mexico.

So I dragged the rear brake to control the rear suspension.

That might work for you, if you want to go into a corner in a higher gear
dragging the rear brake slightly and downshift before driving out of the
corner.

Downshifting after the apex will annoy the shit out of riders on a race
course,
but what does it matter, if you're not on a race course?

